<tr><td scope="row" class='awrnc'><a class="awr" name="09fdhh239x0yc"></a>09fdhh239x0yc</td><td class='awrnc'><pre_sqltext class="awr">WITH   awr_evts as   (SELECT e.event_id,  e.wait_class FROM  WRH$_EVENT_NAME e    WHERE  e.dbid = :dbid) , en as   (SELECT event_id,  nvl(v.wait_class,  awr_evts.wait_class) as wait_class    FROM   awr_evts FULL OUTER JOIN  V$EVENT_NAME v  USING(event_id)    UNION ALL    SELECT 0 as event_id,  'CPU' as wait_class FROM DUAL   ) SELECT * FROM ( SELECT  count(*) as cnt ,          a.SQL_ID,  a.CON_DBID,          sum(decode(a.wait_time,  0,  0,  1)) as on_cpu,          sum(case when a.wait_time = 0 and en.wait_class = 'User I/O'             then 1 else 0 end) as io_wait,          sum(case when a.wait_time = 0 and en.wait_class = 'Cluster'             then 1 else 0 end) as cl_wait,          sum(decode(bitand(a.time_model, power(2,  4)), 0, 0, NULL, 0, 1))             as in_parse,          sum(decode(bitand(a.time_model, power(2,  14)), 0, 0, NULL, 0, 1))
        as in_java,          sum(decode(bitand(a.time_model, power(2,  11)+power(2,  12)),                           NULL, 0, 0, 0, 1)) as in_pls,          max(a.sql_opcode) as opcode,          sum(case when a.qc_session_id &lt;&gt; 0                   and a.qc_session_id &lt;&gt; a.session_id                   and a.qc_instance_id &lt;&gt; 0                   and a.qc_instance_id &lt;&gt; a.instance_number                  then 1 else 0 end) as pq_cnt,          count(distinct nvl(a.sql_plan_hash_value,  0)) as plans,      count(distinct decode(nvl(a.sql_plan_hash_value,  0),  0,  1,  0))                   as noplan  FROM  WRH$_ACTIVE_SESSION_HISTORY a ,  en  WHERE  a.dbid = :dbid  AND a.snap_id &gt; :bid AND a.snap_id &lt;= :eid  AND en.event_id = decode(a.wait_time,  0,  a.event_id,  0)  AND a.sql_id is NOT NULL  AND a.session_type = 1  AND en.wait_class &lt;&gt; 'Idle'  GROUP BY a.SQL_ID,  a.CON_DBID  HAVING count(*) &gt;= :rowcnt ORDER BY count(*) DESC,  a.SQL_ID ASC ) WHERE rownum
 &lt;= :ret</pre_sqltext></td></tr>

Finding 3: Unusual &quot;User I/O&quot; Wait Event
Impact is .89 active sessions, 15.99% of total activity.
--------------------------------------------------------
Wait event &quot;Datapump dump file I/O&quot; in wait class &quot;User I/O&quot; was consuming
significant database time.

Instances that were significantly affected by this finding:
    Number  Name     Percent Impact  ADDM Task Name
    ------  -------  --------------  --------------
    1       testdb1  100             ADDM:2853865951_1_650

   Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .89 active sessions, 15.99% of total activity.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the cause for high &quot;Datapump dump file I/O&quot; waits. Refer to
      Oracle&apos;s &quot;Database Reference&quot; for the description of this wait event.

   Recommendation 2: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .89 active sessions, 15.99% of total activity.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the cause for high &quot;Datapump dump file I/O&quot; waits in Module
      &quot;Data Pump Worker&quot;.

   Recommendation 3: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .89 active sessions, 15.99% of total activity.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the cause for high &quot;Datapump dump file I/O&quot; waits in Service
      &quot;testdb.corpdevhkjc.com&quot;.

   Recommendation 4: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .46 active sessions, 8.23% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the cause for high &quot;Datapump dump file I/O&quot; waits with
      P1,P2,P3 (&quot;count, intr, timeout&quot;) values &quot;4&quot;, &quot;256&quot; and &quot;4294967295&quot;
      respectively.

   Recommendation 5: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .28 active sessions, 4.99% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the cause for high &quot;Datapump dump file I/O&quot; waits with
      P1,P2,P3 (&quot;count, intr, timeout&quot;) values &quot;1&quot;, &quot;256&quot; and &quot;4294967295&quot;
      respectively.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class &quot;User I/O&quot; was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is 2.66 active sessions, 47.67% of total activity.

        <a name="CELL_OUTLIER_SUMMARY"/>
        <h3 class="exa">Exadata Outlier Summary</h3>
        <ul class="exa">
            <li class="exab">Exadata Outlier Summary</li>
            <ul class="exa" style="padding-left:20px">
                <li>
                    <a class="exa" href="#OUTLIER_SUMMARY_CELL">Cell Level</a>
                </li>
                <li>

                </li>
            </ul>
        </ul>
        <p>
            <a name="OUTLIER_SUMMARY_CELL"/>
            <h4 class="exa">Outlier Summary - Cell Level</h4>
            <ul>
                <li class="exa">Outliers are cells whose average performance is outside the normal range, where normal range is -/+ 1 standard deviation</li>
                <li class="exa">Outlier cells must have a mininum of 10 IOPs.  Idle cells are not considered for outlier analysis.</li>
                <li class="exa">Outliers for hard disks are displayed when Hard Disk IOPs exceeds 78.12
        (1% of maximum capacity of 7,812)</li>
                <li class="exa">Outliers for flash disks are displayed when Flash Disk IOPs exceeds 5175
        (1% of maximum capacity of 517,500)</li>
                <li class="exa">Outliers for flash disks will not be displayed.  There are only 4,936 flash IOPs</li>
                <li class="exa">A 'v' and a dark yellow background indicates an outlier value below the low range</li>
                <li class="exa">A '^' and a light red background indicates an outlier value above the high range</li>
                <li class="exa">A '*' and a dark red background indicates over maximum capacity</li>
                <li class="exa">Disk Type &lt;F|H>/&lt;size>: F-Flash, H-Hard Disk</li>
                <li class="exa">Maximum cell capacity for hard disks:
           IOPS: H/3.6T: 2,604 |
           IO MB/s: H/3.6T: 1,800</li>
                <li class="exa">Maximum cell capacity for flash disks:
          IOPS: F/1.5T: 172,500 |
          IO MB/s: F/1.5T: 10,000</li>
                <li>
                    <b>There is insufficient activity on Flash Disks, and Flash Disk outliers will not be displayed</b>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <b>There are no cell outliers on hard disks</b>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
